│ : I->operands()) {\n    // In some cases, we create VPInstructions for          │
│ Instructions that are not in\n    // the original loop, but are still scalar.   │
│ In this case, their operands\n    // are not in the VPlan and we should not try │
│ to create VPValues for them.\n    if (VPValue *V = getVPValue(U))\n             │
│ NewVPInst->addOperand(V);\n  }\n}\n\n// PROPOSED CHANGE STARTS HERE\n// If all  │
│ operands are uniform, the result is also uniform.\nbool AllUniform =            │
│ NewVPInst->getNumOperands() > 0;\nfor (VPValue *V : NewVPInst->operands()) {\n  │
│ VPDef *Def = V->getDef();\n  if (!Def || !Def->isUniform()) {\n    AllUniform = │
│ false;\n    break;\n  }\n}\nif (AllUniform)\n                                   │
│ NewVPInst->setGeneratesPerFirstLaneOnly(true);\n// PROPOSED CHANGE ENDS         │
│ HERE\n\nreturn NewVPInst;\n```\n\nThis change will be applied to                │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlan.cpp`.\n\n### 5. Conclusion\n\nBy adding    │
│ this logic, we correctly mark `VPInstruction`s with all-uniform operands as     │
│ producing a uniform (first-lane-only) result. This aligns the VPlan             │
│ representation with the execution logic's expectations, resolving the assertion │
│ failure. The vectorizer will now be able to correctly handle loop-exit PHIs     │
│ with constant inputs, allowing the provided reproducer and similar cases to be  │
